{
  "family": "Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag Reaction (Remote Functionalization)",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "CCCCN(C)Cl"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "C1CCNC1C"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "O",
      "[H+]"
    ],
    "rationale": "This is a classic and simple example of the Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag reaction. The substrate is N-chloro-N-methylbutan-1-amine. Under acidic conditions (often sulfuric acid), a nitrogen-centered radical is formed, which undergoes a 1,5-hydrogen atom transfer from the delta-carbon. The resulting carbon-centered radical then abstracts the chlorine atom, forming a delta-chloroamine. Subsequent intramolecular nucleophilic substitution upon treatment with base (implied by the workup to the neutral pyrrolidine product) yields the final N-methylpyrrolidine product. This example clearly demonstrates the key steps: N-halogenation, radical formation, intramolecular 1,5-HAT, and cyclization.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses a simple acyclic N-chloroamine that cyclizes to a pyrrolidine derivative. It avoids arenes, complex ring systems, and other reactive functional groups that could cause collisions with other named reactions. The core transformation is the C-H functionalization at a remote (delta) position, which is the defining characteristic of this reaction, distinguishing it from Hofmann elimination or rearrangement."
  }
}
